A triangular continuous random variable.

The probability density function for `triangular` within the interval $[l, r)$
and mode $m$ (where the peak of the distribution occurs) is:

$$
\begin{split}
    f(x; l, m, r) = \begin{cases}
                        \frac{2(x-l)}{(r-l)(m-l)}\quad \text{for $l \leq x \leq m$},\\
                        \frac{2(r-x)}{(r-l)(r-m)}\quad \text{for $m \leq x \leq r$},\\
                        0\quad \text{otherwise}.
                    \end{cases}
\end{split}
$$

A Bernoulli discrete random variable.

The probability mass function for `bernoulli` in terms of the probability
of success $p$ of a single trial is:

$$
\begin{split}
    f(k; p) = \begin{cases}
                        (1-p)\quad \text{if $k = 0$},\\
                        p\quad \text{if $k=1$}\\
                \end{cases}
\end{split}
$$

where $0 \leq p \leq 1$.

